import java.util.*;   // Import the necessary Java utilities classes, such List or Map that we will use for our session manager here below: HashMap<String, String> - a simple key-value store; UUID - generate unique IDs easily within class java_48514_SessionManager_A01 and thus make it suitable to include in your code
import java.util.concurrent.*;  // Import the necessary Java concurrency utilities classes such as ExecutorService for creating threads or tasks that are meant to run, Future<T> which we will use below: Callable - a task with no return value; ScheduledExecutorService and scheduledFutureTask pair is used in case of periodic checks
import java.security.*;  // Import the necessary Java security utilities classes such as MessageDigest for generating unique IDs securely, SecureRandom to generate random password (it'll be more suitable if you have access restrictions on this part)   and also KeyStore - a class which will hold our private key
import javax.crypto.*;  // Import the necessary Java cryptography utilities classes such as Cipher for encrypting/decrypting data, SecretKey to store secret keys (we'll use AES here). Also Certificate is needed if you have some certificates involved in this part of system:
import javax.mail.*;  // If we want sending emails then Import EmailUtils - an utility class which includes methods for email send and receive such as, SMTPTransport or MimeMessage used to construct the message body (MIME messages) that are meant from one server's sender address to another; Authenticator is needed if you have some authentication details involved.
import javax.*;  // Import everything related jar file: JComponent for GUI and JOptionPane/JDialog, Swing or JavaFX frameworks as per requirement (if any). But in this case since it's a legacy style program where we only use standard libraries that can be used without requiring external dependencies then omitted.